h. Europe, where Jews had dreamed of return, has become the new ruined shrine: The literary pilgrimages of these writers recall familiar patterns of grieving and representation and a tentative reinvention of the diasporic imagination–in America, of course, but, paradoxically, even in Zion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aJewish diaspora in literature. 0aJewish literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aZionism in literature. 4aChristianity. 4aJewish studies. 4aJudaism. 4aexile. 4apilgrim. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520918214?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520918214423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520918214/original  aEBA_EMB  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles